<div class="content">
  <div class="text">
          <p>The ocean, a vast and mysterious expanse, covers more than 70% of our planet's surface. It is a world of wonder, teeming with life and brimming with secrets yet to be uncovered. From its deepest trenches to its sunlit surface, the ocean plays a crucial role in sustaining life on Earth.</p>
          <p>Beneath the waves lies an array of ecosystems, each more diverse than the last. Coral reefs, often referred to as the rainforests of the sea, are bustling with vibrant marine life. These underwater cities provide shelter, food, and breeding grounds for countless species, from the smallest plankton to the largest predators.</p>
    
          <p>The ocean is also a key player in regulating the Earth's climate. It absorbs a significant portion of the carbon dioxide we produce and generates over half of the world's oxygen through the photosynthesis of phytoplankton. The currents that flow through the ocean, such as the Gulf Stream, distribute heat around the globe, influencing weather patterns and climates.</p>
    
      <p>Exploring the ocean has always been a challenge due to its depth and pressure. However, advancements in technology have allowed us to venture further and learn more. Submersibles and remote-operated vehicles (ROVs) have reached the deepest parts of the ocean, like the Mariana Trench, revealing new species and geological formations.</p>
</div>
